SVS-FLAMEFLOW v1.0
Self-Verifying Science Protocol for Fluid and Combustion Systems
================================================================

OVERVIEW
--------
SVS-FLAMEFLOW v1.0 is a deterministic verification protocol for validating
fluid and combustion models using calibration-locked residual bounds and
invariant physical constraints.

It is not a simulator.
It is not a CFD engine.
It is not a combustion solver.

It is a scientific verification layer.

Its purpose is to determine whether a model is physically admissible and
consistent with measured data under instrument-defined noise limits.

----------------------------------------------------------------

FUNDAMENTAL RULE
----------------
For each measurement channel k:

    r_k = RMSE(O_k - Ohat_k) / sigma_k

Where:

    O_k       = observed sensor measurements
    Ohat_k    = model predictions
    sigma_k   = standard deviation of measurement noise (from calibration)
    alpha     = fixed tolerance multiplier (default = 3.0)

Acceptance condition:

    r_k < alpha     for all channels k

Tolerance definition:

    epsilon_k = alpha * sigma_k

epsilon is defined strictly from calibration and is locked before fitting.
It may not be modified after fitting.

----------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT FLAMEFLOW GUARANTEES
--------------------------
If a model passes SVS-FLAMEFLOW v1.0, then:

1) It agrees with measured data within calibration-defined noise bounds.
2) It satisfies physical admissibility constraints.
3) It cannot pass through post-hoc tolerance manipulation.
4) Its configuration is cryptographically pinned.
5) Its verification record is append-only and auditable.

----------------------------------------------------------------

CALIBRATION REQUIREMENTS
-------------------------
Each sensor must provide:

    sensor_id
    channel
    gain
    offset
    sampling_rate
    sigma (noise estimate)
    timestamp
    calibration_method

sigma must originate from calibration experiments.
sigma must NOT be derived from model residuals.

epsilon is computed only as:

    epsilon_k = alpha * sigma_k

----------------------------------------------------------------

MULTI-CHANNEL VERIFICATION
---------------------------
All channels must pass simultaneously.

Typical channels include:

    pressure
    temperature
    flow_rate
    velocity
    species fractions
    turbulence quantities

Passing one channel while failing another is not permitted.

----------------------------------------------------------------

PHYSICAL ADMISSIBILITY CONSTRAINTS
-----------------------------------
Minimum constraint set:

    density >= 0
    temperature >= 0
    species_fraction_i >= 0
    sum(species_fractions) = 1
    turbulence_k >= 0         (if used)
    eddy_viscosity >= 0       (if used)

Optional extensions may include:

    conservation_of_mass
    conservation_of_momentum
    conservation_of_energy
    PDE residual norms
    entropy inequalities

Any constraint violation results in failure.

----------------------------------------------------------------

ANTI-OVERFIT GATES
------------------
Optional verification gates:

    holdout_verification_ok
    reproducibility_ok

If enabled, both must be true for acceptance.

----------------------------------------------------------------

SETUP HASH
----------
Each verification computes:

    setup_hash = SHA256(
        geometry +
        calibration_packet +
        constraint_manifest +
        objective_spec
    )

The setup_hash guarantees:

    configuration immutability
    constraint immutability
    tolerance immutability
    objective immutability

Any modification produces a new hash.

----------------------------------------------------------------

RUN RECORD
----------
Each verification produces a RunRecord containing:

    experiment_id
    protocol_id
    timestamp
    operator
    setup_hash
    solver metadata
    fitted parameters
    residual summary
    constraint violations
    verdict
    reason codes

RunRecords are append-only and typically stored in JSONL format.

----------------------------------------------------------------

PASS / FAIL LOGIC
-----------------
Failure occurs if any of the following are triggered:

    FAIL_CALIBRATION
    FAIL_OBSERVABILITY
    FAIL_CONSTRAINT
    FAIL_RESIDUAL_THRESHOLD
    FAIL_OVERFIT
    FAIL_REPRODUCIBILITY
    FAIL_NUMERICS
    FAIL_CLOSURE_MODEL

Pass occurs only if none of the above are triggered.

----------------------------------------------------------------

WHAT FLAMEFLOW IS NOT
----------------------
FlameFlow is not:

    a CFD solver
    a combustion chemistry engine
    a numerical integrator
    a simulation package

It verifies the scientific validity of such systems.

----------------------------------------------------------------

INTENDED APPLICATIONS
----------------------
    combustion validation
    CFD verification
    hydrogen flame research
    gas turbine validation
    internal combustion research
    experimental reproducibility enforcement
    scientific audit systems

----------------------------------------------------------------

PROTOCOL IDENTITY
------------------
SVS-FLAMEFLOW-v1.0

Any modification to:

    epsilon definition
    residual definition
    constraint set
    objective structure
    pass/fail logic

requires a new protocol version.

----------------------------------------------------------------

PHILOSOPHY
----------
Scientific models frequently fail due to:

    tolerance manipulation
    single-channel fitting
    hidden constraint violations
    silent configuration changes
    overfitting to noise

SVS-FLAMEFLOW prevents these failure modes by binding model acceptance to:

    calibration noise
    invariant constraints
    reproducibility
    cryptographic configuration pinning

Core principle:

    A model is only as valid as the residual it cannot hide.

----------------------------------------------------------------
SVS-FLAMEFLOW v1.0
Self-Verifying Science
----------------------------------------------------------------
